      "title": "Reversible Process",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Reversible Process</strong></h3><p>A process is said to be reversible, if, it is :</p><p>(i) quasi-static</p><p>(ii) Non-dissipative</p><p><strong>(i) Quasi static : </strong>If unique value of $\\text{P},\\text{V}$ and $\\text{T}$ can be specified to a gaseous system at certain moment, then system is said to be in thermodynamic equilibrium. But, in practical, no system can exactly achieve thermodynamic equilibrium because the parts of the system do not at once achieve, the same value of $\\text{P},\\text{V},\\text{T}$.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"224\" height=\"187\"></p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ If the process is carried out very slowly then system will be in almost thermodynamic equilibrium and this process is called quasi-static process.</p><p><strong>(ii) Non-dissipative&nbsp;</strong></p><p>If no heat dissipation takes during the process then it is called non-dissipative.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dbcec03b9dcaf1afe384"
    }
